Make the server Ubuntu!!!!


2. Security Group Rules
RDS Security Group

The RDS MySQL database must allow traffic from the middleware server.

Add this inbound rule to the RDS security group:

Type	Port	Source
MySQL/Aurora	3306	Middleware EC2 security group

Do not open the database to everyone unless it is just for temporary testing.

Middleware EC2 Security Group

The Ubuntu middleware server needs to allow SSH and API traffic.

Add these inbound rules:

Type	Port	Source
SSH	22	Your IP address
Custom TCP	5000	Frontend security group or 0.0.0.0/0 for testing

For testing, port 5000 can temporarily be open to the public. For a cleaner final setup, only allow the frontend server to access it.

3. SSH Into the Ubuntu Middleware Server

From your computer, connect to the Ubuntu EC2 instance:

chmod 400 GE_healthImproved.pem
ssh -i GE_healthImproved.pem ubuntu@YOUR_MIDDLEWARE_PUBLIC_IP

Replace:

YOUR_MIDDLEWARE_PUBLIC_IP

with the public IPv4 address of your Ubuntu EC2 middleware server.

4. Update Ubuntu and Install Required Software

Run:

sudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade -y

Install Python, pip, Git, and virtual environment support:

sudo apt install python3 python3-pip python3-venv git -y
5. Clone the Middleware Repository

Clone the middleware repo:

git clone https://github.com/bas6809/ge-health-aws-middleware-main.git
cd ge-health-aws-middleware-main
6. Create a Python Virtual Environment

Inside the middleware project folder, run:

python3 -m venv venv

Activate it:

source venv/bin/activate

Your terminal should now show something like:

(venv) ubuntu@ip-address:~/ge-health-aws-middleware-main$
7. Install Python Dependencies

Install Flask, Flask-CORS, and PyMySQL:

pip install flask flask-cors pymysql

You can also create a requirements.txt file:

nano requirements.txt

Add:

flask
flask-cors
pymysql

Save the file, then install everything with:

pip install -r requirements.txt
